Steps to reproduce:

* Create project A and some issues on it;
* Create project B ;
* Create a board for project A, create a sprint, add issues to it and start the Sprint;
* Create a board for project B;
* Move one of the issues that are on Sprint 1 of board A to project B;
* Go to Board B - the Sprint 1 will exist there;
* Complete Sprint 1 in Board B - Sprint 1 in Board A will be completed too.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-7710].
  {panel}

The filters for my boards all look like this:

{code}
category = Development AND "Sprint Team" = Rocket OR ORDER BY Rank ASC
{code}

The problem I have is that even if all issues in the current sprint are from projects where the sprint manager has the *Project Administrator* role, the *Complete Sprint* button would still be inactive because there is a single project in the *Development* category that does not have every sprint manager in the *Project Administrator* role. Hence none of my sprint managers would be able to complete a sprint unless I kick the additional project out or give my sprint managers administrator permissions for that project.

The *Complete Sprint* permission should only look at the permission scheme of those projects that actually issues appear on the board for and not at all projects in the category *Development*.

Create a new issue directly via the planning board will throw the error message shown in the attachment screenshot, whilst it doesn't prevent the issue from being created it does present the user with a disconcerting error message.


It seems there is an error in the code as illustrated below:

Error in BacklogController.js at line 616
The current code is:
{code}
var newDef = new $.Deferred();
{code}

But it should be : 
{code}
var newDef = new AJS.$.Deferred();
{code}

The issue seems to be occurred after upgrade the GH plugin.
